Bitbucket online editor handles file character encoding incorrectly

Adding a dot after options for some reason changes a pound sign as well. File was correctly encoded before using the online editor

Looking at diff on bitbucket shows:

{code}
- from just Â£99 per month. Perfect for new and small businesses. 
+ from just £99 per month. Perfect for new and small businesses. 

- options..
+ options...
{code}

*file before commit:*

{code}
file -bi src/pages/index.md
text/html; charset=utf-8
{code}

*file after commit with online editor:*

{code}
file -bi src/pages/index.md
text/html; charset=iso-8859-1
{code}

Modifying a file with local editor correctly changes just that line

{code}
-options...
+options....
{code}

Attached 2 files first before modification, second after modification with online editor

File character encoding should remain utf-8

*Steps to reproduce:*

# Create a new repository on BitBucket
# Initialize a new local git repository according to BitBucket instructions
# Create your first file, commit, and push

{code}
#!python

$ echo "Hello World" >> test.txt
$ git add test.txt
$ git commit -m "Initial commit"
{code}

# Right before pushing, rename the branch "master" to any other (E.g:  "develop")
# Push the branch

{code}
#!python


git push -u origin name_of_your_local_branch
{code}

*Expected result:*\\
The branch page for the repo should show the list of branches for the repo

*Actual result:*\\
The branch page will tell you to "start with a branch"

h3. Summary
When including spaces ("_%20_" / "_+_") within the URL field while perform an API request :

{code}
#!bash
curl -iX POST -u "$user:$password" -d url="http://test.com/test%20test" -d key=build -d state=INPROGRESS &#x27;https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<username>/<Reponame>/commit/46be58e746215a4d2baa5673711be563a531311f/statuses/build/&#x27;
{code}

Bitbucket Cloud Returns with the error below:

{code}
#!bash
{"error": {"fields": {"url": ["Enter a valid URL."]}, "message": "Bad request"}}
{code}

###Expected Results

* 201 Status Code (Able to add the build status successfully)

h3. Notes
Have tested with removing the space and add other symbols (eg. &, %21 etc.) and manage to update the status build.

h3. Workaround 
Use Json format
{code}
curl --request POST \
  --url https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<username>/<Reponame>/commit/46be58e746215a4d2baa5673711be563a531311f/statuses/build/ \
  ---u "$user:$password" \
  -d '{"url":"http://test.com/test%20test", "name":"test-build", "state":"SUCCESSFUL", "key":"test-space2" }'
{code}

Pipelines are triggered by push. There is the possibility to configure a number of other webhooks, e.g. &#x27;on pull request&#x27;. However it is not possible to connect them with a pipeline and disable or reconfigure the default &#x27;Pipelines&#x27; webhook which triggers on push.

If it were possible to have different webhooks as triggers and distinguish between them inside the pipeline it would enable:

* to configure different pipelines for different events (webhooks), e.g.:

{code}
 - just unit tests with fast feedback loop for every change on feature branch,

 - heavy, time consuming quality assurance for pull request;
{code}
* better integration with "Sonar for Bitbucket Cloud", especially with respect to the "Shows Sonar code issues in pull requests" feature

This format of URL in the Issue description should link to the file&#x27;s source page and highlight line 4 to 6 of the file:

{{[Link](https://bitbucket.org/username/repositoryname/src/randomhashexample167thsn72ajsnjas/filename.txt?at=branchname&fileviewer=file-view-default#filename.txt-4:6)}}

This link should work in the issue description even if its changed from the colon to "%3A" - yet although it still links to the correct page, it just links to the file in general, as if the line selection wasn&#x27;t there. It ignores the parameters.
